🟡 **Medium** — Template literal allocation on every cache lookup

**Impact:** `\`${partitionCount}:${partitionKey}\`` creates a new heap string on **every** call — including cache hits — partially undermining the purpose of the cache, which is to avoid allocations on the hot path.

**Fix:** Use a two-level `Map<string, Map<number, number>>` keyed first by `partitionKey`, then by `partitionCount`. Cache hits then require only two `Map.get` calls with no string concatenation:

```ts
const partitionKeyToIdCache = new Map<string, Map<number, number>>();

const inner = partitionKeyToIdCache.get(partitionKey);
if (inner) {
  const id = inner.get(partitionCount);
  if (id !== undefined) return id;
}
```

This removes the per-call string allocation entirely.

🟢 **Low** — `body.trim()` allocates a new string on every decoded message

**Impact:** `String.prototype.trim()` returns a new string object even when there is no leading/trailing whitespace (which is the common case for well-formed AMQP payloads). At high message throughput (thousands of receives per second), this adds one unnecessary heap allocation per message.

**Fix:** Scan for the first non-whitespace character with an index rather than allocating a trimmed copy. Only the first character (and the full string for `"true"/"false"/"null"` literals) needs inspection:

```ts
function looksLikeJson(body: string): boolean {
  let start = 0;
  while (start < body.length && (body[start] === " " || body[start] === "\t" ||
         body[start] === "\n" || body[start] === "\r")) {
    start++;
  }
  if (start === body.length) return false;
  const first = body[start];
  switch (first) {
    case "{": case "[": case '"': return true;
    case "t": return body.trimEnd() === "true";
    case "f": return body.trimEnd() === "false";
    case "n": return body.trimEnd() === "null";
    // ...
  }
}
```

For `{`, `[`, and `"` (the dominant cases) no allocation is needed at all.
